Exercise 2: Factor management

Task: Choose one dataset (of your choice) and a variable to explore. After ensuring the variable(s) you are exploring are indeed factors, you should:

str(gapminder$continent)
##  Factor w/ 5 levels "Africa","Americas",..: 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 ...

2.1: Drop factor / levels

gapminder$continent %>% 
  nlevels() 
## [1] 5
nrow(gapminder)
## [1] 1704
gapminder_dropped <- gapminder %>% 
  filter(continent == c("Asia", "Europe", "Americas", "Africa")) %>% 
  droplevels()
gapminder_dropped$continent %>% 
  nlevels()
## [1] 4
gapminder_dropped %>% 
  nrow()
## [1] 420

2.2 Reorder levels based on knowledge from data

gap_maxlife <- gapminder_dropped %>% 
  group_by(continent, country) %>% 
  summarize(max_lifeExp = max(lifeExp))
gap_maxlife$country %>% 
  nlevels()
## [1] 140
gap_europe <- gap_maxlife %>% 
  filter(continent == "Europe") %>% 
  droplevels()
gap_europe %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(country, max_lifeExp)) +
  ylab("Maximum life expectancy (yeas)") +
  xlab("Country") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_light()

gap_europe %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(fct_reorder(country, max_lifeExp, min), max_lifeExp)) +
  ylab("Maximum life expectancy (years)") +
  xlab("Country") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_light()

Exercise 4

On Assignment 1 I made the graph shown below. At the time it seemed nice to me, but now that Ive learned how to make pretty and most importantly, informative graphs with ggplot I will change some aspects if it.

old_plot <- ggplot(gapminder, aes(continent, pop)) + 
  geom_col()
new_plot <- gapminder %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(reorder(continent, -pop), pop)) +
  ylab("Population") +
  xlab("Continent") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  theme_light()
plots <- plot_grid(old_plot, new_plot, ncol =,
          labels = c("Old plot", "New plot"))

plots

Task: Use ggsave() to explicitly save a plot to file. Include the exported plot as part of your repository and assignment.

plots_file <- "plots.png" #file name

plot_path <- here::here("hw05", "plots") #path

ggsave(plots_file, plots, device = "png", path = plot_path, width = 10, height = 4)
